[{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

[{"sha":"b32c21eb1b29c8ad7964820dfd0380e4c3671378","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] TensorRT execution context should not retain GPU memory.

Previously, when we create TensorRT execution context, we also allocate the GPU
memory the execution context requires in order to execute the TensorRT engine
associated with the execution context. This GPU memory won't be released until
the execution context is destroyed when the containing TRTEngineOp is
destructed. A TF-TRT converted graph often has multiple execution contexts, due
to multiple TRTEngineOps or multiple execution contexts for a single
TRTEngineOp. For this reason, retaining GPU memory in each execution context
during the graph execution can cause unnecessary excessive GPU memory usage.

This CL delays the allocation of GPU memory for an execution context until the
execution context is used to enqueue a TensorRT engine for execution and
releases the GPU memory when the execution context finishes executing the
TensorRT engine.

This CL leaves unused fields or unused parameters in some data structures or
subroutines. Cleaning up the code will be done in a follow up CL.

[{"sha":"0ae1a36ee0e5002c73555af83717ef142aade5e5","author":{"name":"Richard Uhler","email":"394366297491d0a7105f27d2861637ec705af27e@google.com"},"message":"Add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes attributes on export.

The dtype and shape information for resource arguments has to be handled
specially: GraphDef encodes that information in _handle_dtypes and
_handle_shapes attributes while MLIR encodes that information using
!tf.resource subtypes.

When exporting MLIR to GraphDef, add _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes for resource arguments. This is consistent with import, which
already has a special case for reading the _handle_dtypes and _handle_shapes
attributes on import from GraphDef to MLIR.

This fixes RET_CHECK arg_shape.handle_type != DT_INVALID errors that happen
when converting GraphDef to and from MLIR before passing the graph to the old
TF/XLA bridge.

[{"sha":"bcc08de62e427a7c10b64204bb2b1de252f2dd05","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PR #47767: lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47767

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`)...

[{"sha":"187299f5c03dc1286b6275e1107f012286c4daf5","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Handle AllGather & AllToAll in GpuLayoutAssignment.

- XLA:GPU all-gather implementation can only support all-gathers with the all-gather
  dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Similarly, all-to-all implementation with split_dimensions can only support all-to-all with
  the split dimension being the most major dimension in the physical layout.
- Fix NcclAllGather/AllToAllThunk::CanImplement to correctly check this.
- Fix GpuLayoutAssignment to enforce this constraint by forcing the output
  layout to have the all-gather/split dimension as the most major dimension.
- With this change, we don't need AllGatherDecomposer to handle otherwise
  unsupported all-gathers. If an all-gather is truly unsupported beyond these layout
  constraints that layout assignment takes care of, the all-reduce generated during
  the decomposition of the all-gather will be unsupported as well.
